assistant: - About 13.8 billion years ago, the universe began with the Big Bang, expanding rapidly from a hot, dense state.
- As it cooled, basic particles formed atoms (mostly hydrogen and helium); gravity gathered matter into the first stars.
- Inside stars, fusion created heavier elements (carbon, oxygen, iron); when massive stars exploded as supernovae, they spread these elements.
- Our solar system formed ~4.6 billion years ago from dust and gas around the Sun, leading to Earth and the other planets.
- On Earth, chemistry led to biology, life evolved, and humans emerged, wondering about origins.
- Today the universe is still expanding, dominated by dark matter and dark energy, with billions of galaxies—Earth remains a small blue planet in a vast cosmos.
